I believe your problem lies in the following part of your code:

     while (moneySum &gt; EPS) {

        month = month + 1;
        moneySum = moneySum * (1 + 0.06 / 12);
        moneySum = moneySum - withDraw;

    }
Imagine what happens when ```moneySum``` is very large, at the end of each iteration of the ```while``` loop. Let&#39;s say you input ```moneySum = 1000000```, then it gets updated like so:

    final double withDraw = 500;
    moneySum = 1000000; // from input
    
    while (moneySum &gt; EPS) {
       month = month + 1;
       moneySum = moneySum * (1 + 0.06 / 12); // 1005000
       moneySum = moneySum - withDraw; // 1004500
       // moneySum is now larger than it was before,
       //  it will thus keep increasing indefinitely
    }
After each iteration, ```moneySum``` only increases, but your loop condition checks whether ```moneySum``` decreases to below ```EPS = 0.000000000000001```, which will never happen.

To fix this issue, make sure you account for this possibility in your loop, it&#39;s the special case where you &quot;never run out of money&quot;. Like this:

    while (moneySum &gt; EPS) {
        month = month + 1;
        double newMoneySum = moneySum * (1 + 0.06 / 12) - withDraw;
        if (newMoneySum &lt; moneySum)
            moneySum = newMoneySum;
        else {
            month = -1; // this is so we can check for this condition later
            year = -1;  // feel free to implement it however you like
            break; // this will exit the while loop, regardless of the loop condition
        }
    }

    for (int i = 0; month &gt; 12; i++) {

        month = month / 12;
        year = month + i;

    }
    
    if (year &lt; 0 &amp;&amp; month &lt; 0) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Your money will last you forever!&quot;);
    } else if (year &gt; 0) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Your money will last &quot; + year + &quot; years and &quot; + month + &quot; months&quot;);
    } else if (year &lt;= 0) {
        System.out.println(&quot;your money will last &quot; + month + &quot; months&quot;);
    } else if (month &lt;= 1) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Your money will last &quot; + month + &quot;months&quot;);
    } else if (month == 1 &amp;&amp; year == 1) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Your money will last one year and one month&quot;);
    }

Hope this helps!

Feel free to implement it differently as well, helps with learning :)

